1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 {Straight into one
of the thematic battlegrounds of the world champions! Both Anand and Nakamura
played this way yesterday, and it is not clear who was copying whom.} 7. dxc5
Bxc5 8. Qc2 (8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. a3 Nc6 11. Bd3 {seems to me a
completely logical question: Black has an IQP, and probably will do for the
rest of the game. It is a difficult problem to resolve by dynamic means, as
White will simply meet . ..d4 with e4 (even if there is no trick such as
taking and then Be3.) For instance, White was successful in the following
encounter:} Bb6 12. O-O Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. b4 a6 15. Rc1 d4 16. g4 Bg6 17. e4
Re8 18. Re1 Rc8 19. Bc4 $1 $14 {Svidler,P-Harikrishna,P Shenzhen 2017}) 8...
Nc6 9. a3 {I do not believe that this move (if followed by the next) is
White's most critical idea.} ({Previously I commentated on a Tata Steel game
for this site:} 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. a3 Re8 (10... Be7 {is more common now, and then}
11. Be2 {has a huge score for White; indeed I suspect White is probably
slightly better following} Ne4 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 exd5 14. O-O $14) 11. Nd2
(11. Be2 e5 $15 {is the point}) 11... e5 12. Bg5 Nd4 13. Qb1 $1 (13. Qc1 Bf5 {
is liable to lead to a forced draw.} 14. Bxf6 Nc2+ 15. Ke2 Nd4+ $11 {Carlsen,
M-Nakamura,H Douglas 2017}) 13... Bf5 14. Bd3 $14 {Mamedyarov,S-Anand,V Wijk
aan Zee 2018}) 9... Qa5 10. O-O-O {Possibly White thinks that because he has
previously found a good idea for Black in this line that he knows it better
than his opponent, but this was proven incorrect.} ({Of course,} 10. Rd1 {
was still possible.}) (10. Ra2 $5 {was the move chosen in a Topalov game, and
it might be a good try for an edge.} Be7 11. b4 Qd8 12. h3 b6 (12... d4 $1 $11)
13. cxd5 exd5 14. Be2 Be6 15. Ng5 Rc8 $6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Ba6 $14 {Topalov,
V-Nakamura,H Saint Louis 2017}) (10. Nd2 Bb4 $5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb3 Bxc3+ 13.
bxc3 Qd8 $132 {could have been a decent try for an edge in Topalov,V-Nakamura,
H Paris 2017, notwithstanding that it ultimately failed}) 10... Ne4 (10... Bd7
{is logical, but here the thematic} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ng5 {might objectively
give White a little something (despite the terribly un-human nature of opening
a file with one's queen and king on.)}) 11. Nb5 (11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Bxa3
13. bxa3 Qxa3+ 14. Kd2 Rd8+ 15. Ke2 Qb2+ 16. Rd2 Rxd2+ 17. Nxd2 e5 18. Bg3 Bg4+
$3 19. f3 (19. Qxg4 Rd8 20. Kf3 Qxd2 21. Bh4 f5 22. Qg5 Rd4 $1 $11 {leads to
perpetual check.}) 19... Rd8 20. Be1 Bh5 $13 {In January I wrote: The mess
continues, and White has a few moves now, but I don't think there will be any
way found for him to keep an edge. I retain the same opinion.}) 11... a6 12.
Nc7 e5 $1 {Originally played by Karjakin and also mentioned in my notes to the
above-referenced game.} 13. Rxd5 $1 (13. Nxd5 {is tricky, but probably
eventually nothing for White.} Nxf2 $1 (13... exf4 14. Qxe4 fxe3 15. fxe3 h6
16. Nd4 $16 {Ivanchuk,V-Karjakin, S Medias 2017}) 14. Ng5 $1 (14. Qxf2 exf4 15.
Nxf4 b5 $40) 14... Bf5 $1 15. Qxf2 (15. Qxf5 g6 $17) 15... f6 16. Nh3 exf4 17.
Nhxf4 Ne5 $44 {Black has full compensation for the pawn.}) 13... exf4 $1 (13...
Nxf2 14. Qxf2 Qxc7 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Qc6 17. Bd4 $1 $14) (13... f5 $2 14.
Rxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Ra7 16. Nd5 $16 {Kasparov,G-Vaganian,R Debrecen 1992}) 14.
Qxe4 Qxc7 15. Rxc5 fxe3 16. Bd3 {So far it is quite encouraging to see that
both players agree with my analysis!} (16. Qxe3 b6 17. Rh5 Bg4 18. Rg5 Rfe8 $1
$11) 16... g6 17. fxe3 {The new move, but not a particularly amazing one.} (17.
Qxe3 b6 18. Rg5 (18. Rh5 Bg4 19. Rh4 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Ne5 $132) 18... Na5 $13 {
Black will follow up by hitting the c4-pawn repeatedly, and White does not
have enough attacking firepower to ignore the threats. Therefore he must
retreat and admit to equality.}) 17... Be6 $1 18. Qh4 (18. Ng5 Qd6 19. Nxe6
fxe6 20. Rh5 Rf5 $1 $11) 18... Rae8 (18... Qd6 {is most natural, of course.
I'm not sure what the evaluation should be after} 19. Ng5 h5 20. Qe4 (20. Ne4
Qxd3 21. Nf6+ Kg7 22. Nxh5+ gxh5 23. Rg5+ Qg6 $15) 20... Rfe8 $1 {but it is
axiomatic that with such bad pawns White cannot be better. For instance:} 21.
Nxe6 Rxe6 22. Rd5 Qe7 23. Qf4 Rxe3 $11) 19. Be4 $5 (19. Rd1 {could have been
better.} Bc8 20. e4 b6 21. Rd5 Ne7 {and now there are various repetitions, but
to play on White could maybe try the unclear exchange sacrifice} 22. Kb1 $5)
19... Qb6 $5 {Initiating forced lines.} 20. Qh6 f5 21. Ng5 Rf7 22. Bd5 Bxd5 23.
Rxd5 Qxe3+ 24. Kb1 Rfe7 25. Rhd1 Qe2 26. h4 $4 {A bad mistake, perhaps the
fault of memory, because it is a very strange miscalculation for this level.} (
26. Rd6 Qxc4 27. Rxg6+ hxg6 28. Qxg6+ Kh8 $11 {is simply a draw.}) 26... Ne5 $1
{Now Black is essentially winning.} 27. Nf3 Qe4+ 28. Ka2 Qxc4+ 29. Ka1 Ng4 30.
Qc1 Qxc1+ 31. Rxc1 Kg7 32. h5 $2 {A second bad move with the same pawn, but
this time the position was of course already bad.} Nf6 {Black will soon have
two extra pawns and so White resigned.} 0-1

